[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Clement for his comments. Dr Clement again makes the point, as he has in the past, that HFRS occurs in the Americas and SEOV should be included in a differential diagnosis. Although not mentioned specifically, the Fox 8 report in the previous post mentions deer mice (_Peromyscus maniculatus_), the reservoir rodent of SNV, but does not indicate that the patient had contact with the mice or areas where the mice were present nor mentions brown rats (_Rattus norvegicus_), the rodent reservoir of SEOV. Testing for proteinuria and microhematuria that Dr Clement proposes are simple 1st steps on the road to diagnosis. Routine laboratory serological tests that can differentiate SEOV and SNV or ANDV are important as well. The distribution and habitats of the 3 rodent reservoir species are different and measures that people should take to avoid contact with them and exposure to the viruses that they carry are correspondingly different. SEOV infections in the Americas should not be misdiagnosed. - Mod.TY]
